qas.question: What do deuterostomes and protostomes have in common?

answers.text: both groups possess a complete digestive tract

qas.question: In which group does the anus form first, with the mouth developing secondarily?
What is the process in which cells fill in the interior of the gastrula to form the mesoderm called?
What is the process in which the mesoderm is formed through invagination of the endoderm called?
What do deuterostome embryos undergo during cell division?

context: Deuterostomes differ from protostomes in several ways. Animals from <a0_0>both groups possess a complete digestive tract<a0_0/>. However, in protostomes, the first opening of the gut to appear in embryological development (the archenteron) develops into the mouth, with the anus forming secondarily. In <a1_0>deuterostomes<a1_0/> the anus forms first, with the mouth developing secondarily. In most protostomes, cells simply fill in the interior of the gastrula to form the mesoderm, called <a2_0>schizocoelous development<a2_0/>, but in deuterostomes, it forms through invagination of the endoderm, called <a3_0>enterocoelic pouching<a3_0/>. Deuterostome embryos undergo <a4_0>radial cleavage<a4_0/> during cell division, while protostomes undergo spiral cleavage.
